# Module outline — machine source for themed PPTX (module-slides)
title: "Module 03 — Absolute vs relative paths"
footer: "learn_unix — paths"
slides:
  - type: title
    title: "Absolute vs relative paths"
    subtitle: "Module 03 · learn_unix"
    notes: |
      By the end of this short clip, you'll know when a path is absolute
      and when it's relative — and why that matters after you change directories.

  - type: bullets
    title: "Absolute paths"
    bullets:
      - "Start from the filesystem root"
      - "Do not depend on your current folder"
      - "Same target no matter where you stand"
    notes: |
      An absolute path names the target from the root of the filesystem.
      It does not care which directory you are in right now.

  - type: bullets
    title: "Browser lab track"
    bullets:
      - "Open the paths lab from the tools page"
      - "Load the starter example"
      - "Resolve a few relative cases after cd"
    notes: |
      In the browser lab track, open the absolute-versus-relative paths lab
      from the tools page, load the starter, and try resolving a path after
      you change the working directory.

  - type: bullets
    title: "Real terminal track"
    bullets:
      - "Enter this module's paths example"
      - "Print the working directory"
      - "Move with .. and watch the path change"
    notes: |
      In the real terminal track, go into this module's paths example folder,
      print the working directory, then move up a level and notice how a
      relative path would point somewhere new.

  - type: bullets
    title: "Your turn"
    bullets:
      - "Finish Track A or Track B checklist"
      - "Explain abs vs rel in your own words"
    notes: |
      Pause the video, complete at least one track on the checklist, and
      explain absolute versus relative paths in your own words.
